 modern self-understanding.As he elaborates the idea of weak ontology and the broad criteria behind it, White shows how these are already at work in the thought of contemporary writers of seemingly very different perspectives: George Kateb, Judith Butler, Charles Taylor, and William Connolly. Among these thinkers, often thought to be at odds, he exposes the commonalities that emerge around the idea of weak ontology. In its identification of a critical turn in political theory, and its nuanced explanation of that turn, his book both demonstrates and underscores the strengths of weak ontology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aOntology. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAlthusser, Louis.  aBentham, Jeremy.  aCaputo, John.  aDeleuze, Gilles.  aDerrida, Jacques.  aDewey, John.  aEmersonians.  aEreignis (Heidegger).  aFoucault, Michel.  aFreud, Sigmund.  aGelassenheit (Heidegger).  aGestell (Heidegger).  aHabermas, Jürgen.  aHeidegger, Martin.  aJohnson, Samuel.  aKristeva, Julia.  aKymlicka, Will.  aLarmore, Charles.  aLyotard, Jean-François.  aMacIntyre, Alasdair.  aMilosz, Czeslaw.  aMoon, J. Donald.  aRawls, John.  aRorty, Richard.  aSchopenhauer, Arthur.  aSkinner, Quentin.  aSpivak, Gayatri.  aStrauss, Leo.  aVoegelin, Eric.  aWalzer, Michael.  aWhitman, Walt.  aWittig, Monique.  aabundance: fugitive.  aautonomy, individual: cultural integrity and (Taylor).  abody, the: Butler’s account of.  aconscience: formation of (Butler).  acultivation: of critical responsiveness.  aculture: good of a (Taylor).  aepiphany (Taylor).  aexistence: attachment to (Kateb).  ainterpellation: of Althusser.  aontology, strong.  aontology: in Butler.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University